<br>
Fast forwarding several hundred years, guns were the tool of choice in defending one's property in a time of frontier justice and law.  When government could not protect the land of the citizens, the gun allowed a homesteader to keep poachers/thieves off of his land.  As far as I know, this is a unique situation- and very much at the heart of this &quot;firearms are needed to protect my XYZ&quot; spirit.<br>
<br>
Moving on again, with the immigration boom, and the influx of different cultures (many fighting for  limited job opportunities) so too came a renewed need for weapons.  Public servants, such as the police, could care less if one immigrant family was killed, or stolen from, by another- they didn't have the resources to keep the peace.  This &quot;need&quot; for firearms has continued evolving at every stage in US history.  Very often people who are disenfranchised find the only source of respect and power on the street is in owning, and flaunting, a gun of some sort.<br>
<br>
At every step we've had guns, and this possession has become a social norm.  Personally, I don't think attacking a constitutional right will negate any of the... negatives that our country has with the ownership of firearms.  Beyond the occasional child losing his or her face after poking into his parent's ill-kept weaponry, our problems are mostly with those who own firearms beyond the law, and who would own firearms regardless of whether or not we had a law allowing the sale of them.<br>
<br>
They say &quot;Guns don't kill people, People kill people;&quot; I would have to amend that.  People kill people *because* the system we live in promotes murder.  It is hardly surprising that welfare states in Europe are utopian in comparison to the USA.   Our &quot;American Way&quot; however prevents this, as we constantly enforce social inequality, through inheritance, dog-eat-dog economics etc.  It is hardly surprising that there is a &quot;need&quot; to own a weapon, if that weapon is needed to hold up a store to earn money because there is no other way to, or if the only way to get street cred is to wave a weapon about.<br>
<br>
Amending the Constitution, which in its own right is *More* American than not, will hardly impact the bad effects of weapons in our country.  We'd get a bunch of annoyed gun owners, an overstock of unshot clay pigeons, a dangerous overpopulation of deer, and perhaps a few less homicides and accidental injuries- but it wouldn't eliminate the problem.  If you think people have an easy time smuggling narcotics into the USA, you can imagine how much easier it would be to smuggle guns in.  What exactly would a &quot;Gun Dog&quot; sniff?<br>
